    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix array bounds violation in X2 setup request processing\n\n### Summary\nThe X2 setup request processing functions in the RRC layer contain an off-by-one error in boundary checking that can lead to out-of-bounds array access. When the number of neighboring cells reaches the maximum limit (MAX_NUM_NEIGH_CELLs = 6), the current boundary check using `>` allows the code to proceed and increment the counter, causing access to `neigh_cells_id[6][i]` which is outside the valid array bounds [0-5].\n\nThis can result in memory corruption or segmentation faults under certain network conditions when processing X2 setup messages from neighboring eNBs.\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce this issue:\n1. Configure an eNB with 6 neighboring cells (at maximum capacity)\n2. Trigger an X2 setup request or response from a new neighboring eNB\n3. Observe that the boundary check fails to prevent the increment of `num_neigh_cells` beyond the array bounds\n4. The code will attempt to write to `neigh_cells_id[6][i]` causing undefined behavior\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/RRC/LTE/rrc_eNB.c`: \n  - In `rrc_eNB_process_x2_setup_request()` at line 3646, changed boundary check from `>` to `>=`\n  - In `rrc_eNB_process_x2_setup_response()` at line 3665, changed boundary check from `>` to `>=`\n\nThese changes ensure that when `num_neigh_cells` reaches `MAX_NUM_NEIGH_CELLs`, the functions properly return with an error instead of incrementing the counter and causing out-of-bounds array access.\n"
}